      <section eId="section_3">
        <heading>What are the policy objectives and the intended effects?</heading>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.08in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What are the policy objectives and the intended effects?</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• The new model for importing goods was designed to balance the need for effective border controls with the need to support businesses with import processes that are as simple as possible. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• The measures are intended to meet three objectives:</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">- Improve HMRC and Border Force’s ability to identify and stop high harm goods being brought into the country. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">- Reduce the administrative burden for businesses required to submit ENS declarations and facilitate the flow of legitimate trade.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">- Meet the UK’s international commitments to require S&amp;S declarations on all imports entering GB and treat all trading partners equally.</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_4">
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.08in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? Please justify preferred option (further details in Evidence Base)</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• Two measures are being introduced: </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">- <b>Ending the temporary waiver for ENS declarations on imports from the EU into Great Britain (GB) from 31 January 2025.</b> The data from ENS declarations will provide critical intelligence to HMRC and Border Force to support better targeting of illicit goods. Maintaining the waiver (the ‘do nothing’ option) is not viable as it would not meet the UK’s international obligations and would limit HMRC and Border Force’s ability to risk-assess EU imports as they arrive in GB.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">- <b>Reducing the minimum dataset required to complete an ENS declaration on imports into GB.</b> Businesses will have the option to submit additional data, which will improve HMRC and Border Force’s ability to risk the goods and reduce the chance of legitimate goods being held unnecessarily at the GB border. Maintaining the existing data requirements (the ‘do nothing’ option) was not taken forward, as the previous government reviewed the data requirements and identified opportunities to reduce the administrative burden without undermining the UK’s ability to secure the border. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• There are no non-legislative options to achieve the desired outcomes.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </section>
