        <num>1.</num>
        <content>
          <p>S&amp;S declarations are used by HMRC and Border Force to risk-assess goods before they arrive in, or leave, the UK. The measures discussed in this IA relate only to S&amp;S import declarations (also known as Entry Summary, or ENS, declarations). The UK’s approach to S&amp;S is in line with the World Customs Organisation’s (WCO) SAFE Framework of standards, which requires the pre-arrival or pre-departure collection and risking of information for all consignments entering or exiting a territory. The SAFE Framework provides a global approach to the provision of security data, adopted as a result of the 9/11 terrorist attack in the United States. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>2.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The previous government took a phased approach to introducing import requirements on imports from the EU, recognising the need to give businesses sufficient time to prepare and ensure supply-chains have time to adapt. To date, ENS declarations have not been required on imports from the EU, and a new border model covering S&amp;S and Sanitary and Phytosanitary imports (SPS) was published in August 2023. The current government has delayed the introduction of ENS requirements on EU imports until 31 January 2025, with early submission encouraged before 31 January 2025 if businesses are ready to do so. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>3.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The government has assessed the provisions within the SI and has concluded that one of the proposed facilitations has net direct costs to businesses that fall within Better Regulation reporting requirements. The impact of the dataset reduction is a benefit while the removal of the waiver on imports from the EU is a cost. The net cost on industry is above £5m and therefore we are providing this IA for scrutiny.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Rationale and evidence to justify the level of analysis used in the IA (proportionality approach)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>4.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This IA analysis incorporates policy assumptions from engagement with industry and survey data specifically pertaining to the S&amp;S submission process. The methods have been quality assured as well as discussed with colleagues across government. We provide ranges where there is particular uncertainty, reflected in the final figures.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Description of options considered.</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><u>Legislative option</u></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>5.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Two measures are being introduced:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>i.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Ending the temporary waiver for ENS declarations on EU imports into GB.</b> The data from ENS declarations will provide critical intelligence to HMRC and Border Force to support better targeting of illicit goods, and so that fewer consignments of legitimate trade are stopped unnecessarily.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>ii.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Reducing the minimum dataset required to complete an ENS declaration for all imports into GB. </b>There will be 20 mandatory fields, which are needed for security and allow government risking and targeting systems to operate effectively. There are also up to 8 conditional fields, which need to be completed in certain circumstances. Businesses will have the option to submit an additional 9 fields if it is<b> </b>better for their dataflows or to give HMRC and Border Force additional assurance on the goods, which will also reduce the chance of legitimate goods being held unnecessarily at the GB border. The full 37-data field set is the same as the existing requirements, so businesses can maintain their existing processes (if they already submit ENS declarations) if they choose to do so. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><u>‘Do nothing’ (counterfactual)</u></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>6.</num>
        <content>
          <p>For the purposes of this Impact Assessment, the ‘do nothing’ scenario is used to assess the impact of the legislation. If no legislation was introduced, the temporary waiver for ENS declarations on imports from the EU into GB and the existing mandatory data requirements would remain in place.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>7.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Maintaining the waiver is not viable as it would not meet the UK’s international obligations and would limit HMRC and Border Force’s ability to risk-assess EU imports as they arrive in GB.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>8.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Maintaining the existing data requirements was not taken forward, as the previous government reviewed the data requirements and identified opportunities to reduce the administrative burden without undermining the UK’s ability to secure the border.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Non-legislative options</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>9.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are no non-legislative options to achieve the desired outcomes. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Policy objective</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>10.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are three objectives for these measures:</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>i.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Improve HMRC and Border Force’s ability to identify and stop high harm goods being brought into the country. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>ii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Reduce the administrative burden for businesses required to submit ENS declarations and facilitate the flow of legitimate trade.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>iii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Meet the UK’s international commitments to require S&amp;S declarations on all imports into GB and treat all trading partners equally.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>11.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Indicators of success will be high compliance rates on ENS declarations requirements, and subsequently better risking and fewer high harm goods entering the country. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary and preferred option with description of implementation plan</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>12.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The measures will be given effect by secondary legislation and the publication of a public notice which will come into force on 31 January 2025. The public notice will set out the new ENS requirements dataset, so businesses are clear on their obligations.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>13.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The government has updated gov.uk guidance on ENS declarations to reflect the change in requirements, and has engaged extensively with stakeholders including ports, airports, and hauliers amongst others to prepare them for the new requirements and encourage businesses importing from the EU to submit declarations as soon as they are ready. Stakeholders will continue to be informed of the changes through government communication channels.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Costs and benefits estimation</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>14.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This policy is expected to impact on the cost placed on businesses to comply with information requirements stemming from government regulation. This impact assessment therefore only presents costs faced by businesses specifically related to preparing and submitting these declarations.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>15.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The removal of the ENS waiver for imports from the EU creates a new cost. The cost for both EU and non-EU imports is reduced by the availability of a reduced dataset. There is also a benefit to businesses from fewer legitimate consignments of goods being stopped for examination through better data provision, which is not quantified in this impact assessment.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>16.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Carriers will be required to submit ENS declarations on EU imports for the first time from 31 January 2025, although Home Office and HMRC have encouraged businesses to submit declarations as soon as they are ready to do so. This is estimated to cost £1582.2m over the first 10 years of the policy with discounting adjustments applied to estimated figures to be comparable with other measures presented to any given Parliament. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>17.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The above costs are partially offset by the reduction in the size of the dataset required. Importers from non-EU countries will also see reduced data requirements and therefore reduced costs. The benefits of reduced data requirements is estimated to be £121.2m over a 10-year period after discounting. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>18.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The costs and benefits outlined above combine to a Net Business Impact of £-1446.2m. The detailed methodology used to estimate these is set out in the ‘Detailed methodology’ section below. There are wider benefits, such as to the country as security benefits and to trade as reduced unnecessary interventions at the border by HMRC or Border Force, which are not included in this calculation. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>19.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The estimates presented in this impact assessment are informed by a combination of HMRC internal administrative data sources, commissioned research, online research, informal engagement, and internal analysis. Please refer to Annex A for full details.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>20.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Note, the detailed methodology describes the approach to initially calculate costs and benefits for the original expected start date of the policy (31 October 2024), with adjustments at the end to account for the delay of the policy to 31 January 2025. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Detailed methodology</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Number of S&amp;S declarations</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>21.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The costs of the policy only apply to EU declarations, however HMRC has estimated the expected volume of ENS declarations for both EU and non-EU imports as the benefits affect both and the non-EU volumes inform estimation of the EU volumes. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>22.</num>
        <content>
          <p>HMRC estimated, for 2022, 17.4m ENS declarations for EU dispatches and 11.3m ENS declarations for dispatches from non-EU countries, detailed in the steps below. A breakdown by movement type and region of dispatch is set out in Table 1 below:</p>
        </content>
