      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>23.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This estimate was originally produced in 2022 using data existing at that time. A review of the estimate was performed in the second half of 2024 using an updated methodology and more recent data. The new analysis produced estimates that were broadly similar. Specifically, the older estimate used in this Impact Assessment falls close to the midpoint of the range from the new analysis and firmly within the margins of uncertainty. The decision has thus been taken to retain the pre-existing volume estimates in the model and being reassured that both analyses have compatible results.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Costs</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Overview</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>24.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The HMRC approach to calculating the administrative burden on businesses, which is consistent with the internationally recognised approach in the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) Standard Cost Model, is to multiply the number of declarations by the cost per declaration. Total costs are made up of:</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>iv.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Internal costs (average time taken for data collection and form processing) and </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>v.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Other costs (intermediary fees or charges to access the required software to submit declarations).</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>25.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are different approaches to submitting ENS declarations and usually multiple parties are involved, including the trader, the carrier moving the goods, and potentially a customs intermediary. HMRC’s estimate of the burden covers all resource needed across the import process, including for traders to collect the necessary information and the cost for carriers to submit the declarations. We do not break down cost by the type of business involved, so the cost per declaration is the total cost shared by all businesses involved in the submission.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>26.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The total cost per declaration modelled ranges from £7 to £38 where an additional intermediary is used, and from £4 to £23 where the declarations are completed in-house.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Internal costs</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>27.</num>
        <content>
          <p>HMRC estimated a base internal cost of £10, based on its estimate that it takes normally efficient businesses approximately 36 minutes to collect and prepare the necessary information for an ENS declaration. This is proxied from HMRC survey data that indicates intermediaries take on average 36 minutes to complete ENS declarations. A wage rate of £16.90 is assumed based on the quoted wage for <i>bookkeepers, payroll managers and wages clerks </i>from 2021(taking the median hourly pay excluding overtime from the Office for National Statistics 2021 Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings, and adding a 30% uplift for overhead costs, in accordance with the Standard Cost Model).</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>External costs </i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>28.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Industry research indicates that external costs vary depending on the submission method used:</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>vi.</num>
        <intro>
          <p><u>Intermediary:</u></p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p>For those using an intermediary, 2021 HMRC intermediaries survey data was used, which asks customs intermediaries for the average base price charged to customers to submit ENS declarations. These figures are presented in the following bands: up to £30, more than £30 - £40, more than £40 - £50, more than £50 - £60, more than £60. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p>HMRC takes the mid-points of each band, except for more than £60, which HMRC assumes to be £75, and weight these to each band’s share of respondents, giving £37.93 as the average fee intermediaries charge to customers. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p>HMRC has also conducted desk-based research assessing commercially advertised prices for ENS declarations. The average fee across the six intermediaries HMRC sampled was £26.70. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p>To estimate an average base fee for those using an intermediary, HMRC took the mid-point of the higher £37.93 from the survey and the lower online advertised price of £26.70. This gives an initial submission fee of £32.32 for those using an intermediary.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>vii.</num>
        <intro>
          <p><u>Insourced:</u></p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <intro>
            <p>HMRC assumes that businesses submitting their own ENS declarations still pay for the software to submit. Firms offering declaration submission software online have prices ranging from around £2 to £21 per declaration, dependent on the number of declarations submitted per month. Averaging pricing information from the three firms gives an initial cost of:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>£14.45 per declaration for those using insourced methods submitting a low volume of ENS declarations per year.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>£6.33 submitting a medium volume.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>£4.25 for those submitting a high volume. </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Bulk discounts</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>29.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Significant discounts are advertised for those who submit medium and high volumes of declarations themselves (insourced), where they pay for software to submit declarations. Averaging the discounts across the three, HMRC estimates a 56% reduction for businesses making a medium volume, 71% making a high volume of declarations. Stakeholder feedback with HMRC, Home Office and industry stakeholders suggests that similar discounts exist for those who use intermediaries. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>30.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Therefore, HMRC applied the same discounts to those using an intermediary on the basis that costs are likely to fall for any business submitting declarations for many movements of the same or similar goods, and if they have automated systems.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>31.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The same discounts are applied to ‘internal’ costs, as the costs of collecting and preparing information are likely to decrease for each additional ENS declaration required – for example, if a company is importing the same good repeatedly, they will be able to re-use much of the information from a previous ENS declaration for that good and movement. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Anti-Smuggling nets</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>32.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Some low value consignments (parcels) are treated differently to general freight. HMRC is not currently aware of any parcel operators charging extra for ENS declarations (although the cost may be incorporated into the overall customer price). Moreover, some parcel operators use Anti-Smuggling Nets (ASNs) which share data with HMRC and Border Force so that ENS declarations are not needed. For the internal cost, HMRC believes that the vast majority, if not all, of the data provided to the parcel carrier by the business would be required irrespective of whether an ENS declaration is needed. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>33.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Therefore, for the five largest parcel operators that deal with most consumer parcels, the cost of an ENS for parcel  movements is assumed to be zero for simplicity and due to the very low anticipated cost and lack of any evidence on the precise cost. There are many other parcel operators that offer an express service, but their movements have been treated the same as general freight with the relevant costs applied and included in this IA.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Costs calculations</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>34.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Calculations in the model that use costs for staff are adjusted for expected wage growth using the most recent forecast available from the Office for Budget Responsibility. The standard hourly rate of £16.90 for bookkeepers as discussed above is thus adjusted to its expected value for the year in question when calculating administrative costs. This means that the expected growth in wages over ten years is included in the model.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>35.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Finally, an adjustment is made as EU customs declarations slightly increased between this initial analysis for 2022 and the latest date for which customs declarations volumes are available (2023). This increases the cost by 13%. Declaration volumes are assumed to stay level over the 10-year period of the policy.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>36.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The following calculation adjustments are required for the EANDCB:</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>viii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As the EANDCB covers 10 years, we have extended the costs for ten years from the outset of the policy. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>ix.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We apply a +/-20% ‘low’ and ‘high’ range to the central estimate.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>x.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The RPC EANDCB calculator applies a discounting, meaning costs/ benefits are reduced by 3.5% for each consecutive year in the future. For example, costs in year 2 are reduced by 3.5%. Costs in year 3 are reduced by 7%, and so on. This means the total/average presented at the top of this document will generally be lower than the figures HMRC describes.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>xi.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The table below presents the adjusted figures in 2021 prices. The ‘adjusted central’ figure is the best estimate, after applying discounting to bring the values in line with the first year of the policy, in line with the HMT Green Book. The final figures at the top of this IA have a further adjustment applied which reduces them further to bring them in line with policies made at the start of the parliament in 2020.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>xii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The final figures presented at the top of this IA are further adjusted downwards following standard Impact Assessment practice, to bring to 2019 prices, applying an additional discount factor to bring the policy to 2019, and adjusting for inflation between 2019 and the start of the policy. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>37.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The table below shows the final costs including the adjustments described above.</p>
        </content>
