      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Benefits</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>38.</num>
        <content>
          <p>While the costs of the policy only affect imports from the EU, the reduction in the size of the ENS dataset affects all imports. HMRC has focused on those elements that fall under the administrative burden and which it can quantitatively assess including following OECD standards on the Standard Cost Model as described earlier. This analysis assumes: </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>i.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Reducing the data fields reduces the admin burden.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>ii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The burden is the same for each field on the declaration.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>iii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Reducing data fields is likely to influence internal costs more than external costs.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>iv.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Savings due to dataset reduction which impact internal data gathering costs do not depend on whether declarants are using insourced or outsourced methods.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>v.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Savings are influenced by whether information is uniquely collected for S&amp;S, or also for other customs purposes.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>39.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We have estimated the total reduction in the required burden on businesses due to the dataset reduction. Some businesses may choose to continue submitting ENS declarations with the old requirements. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Whole system considerations</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>40.</num>
        <content>
          <p>A proportion of the goods that arrive in the UK will have travelled through other countries, that is, they are not dispatched directly to the UK. Where this is the case, traders may have to provide the information to multiple jurisdictions. Whilst, from a UK perspective, the costs for ENS declarations will be reduced by making changes to the amount of data or the way in which the data is provided; from the trader perspective it is not as clear that it does make an impact. Therefore, HMRC assumes:</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>i.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Direct movements to GB (where the GB is the first stop) will be in a position to take full advantage of reduced data requirements or other alternative arrangements.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>ii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Indirect movements (goods that arrive at GB via another jurisdiction or good that remain on board when they arrive in GB) may still have to provide S&amp;S information to other authorities, which reduces any potential burden saving. For example, if goods dispatched to the UK from the USA are sent on a ship that stops at Cork (Republic of Ireland), the carrier will be required to make EU S&amp;S declarations in respect of those goods that are bound for the UK. If the data collection cost makes up a high proportion of the overall burden, or if the carrier is charged a single S&amp;S fee that does not vary by route, no longer being required to make a separate GB S&amp;S declaration may save only a minimal amount.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>41.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Non-EU S&amp;S declarations indicate that the proportion of direct movements for non-EU trade is 16%. For EU trade it is assumed that 90% of traffic across all modes is direct. This is because it is anticipated to be more likely that GB will be the first stop after the EU due to geographical considerations.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Methodology</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>42.</num>
        <content>
          <p>HMRC assumes that internal costs (e.g. collecting information and declaration processing) will reduce by the proportion of fields removed, but only where the fields are not still required for other purposes.<i> </i>For example, if a trader is likely to be submitting the same information on a customs declaration, they see no saving from that field’s removal from the ENS declaration. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>43.</num>
        <content>
          <p>For freight remaining on board (FROB), no internal saving is expected as the data would still be required for other customs regimes. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>44.</num>
        <content>
          <p>HMRC assumes that half of external costs are fixed (i.e., not related to the number of fields). HMRC also assumes that if there is a saving, it is proportional to the saving on internal costs. It is assumed that FROB external savings are in line with empty units’ savings. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
