      <paragraph>
        <num>45.</num>
        <content>
          <p>To estimate benefits, the percentages above are multiplied by the declaration costs. Non-EU costs are arrived at using the same methodology as described for EU costs above.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>46.</num>
        <content>
          <p>For the EANDCB calculation, the same steps are taken as for ‘costs,’ described in paragraph 42 above, including increasing EU volumes and hence costs/benefits by 13% (for benefits, from £15m to £17m). The result is shown below, over the first 10 years of the policy. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>47.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The introduction of ENS declarations for EU imports, even combined with the reduction in the data set, is expected to improve data availability, bolster security threat identification, and facilitate the flow of legitimate goods. By improving our ability to detect and intercept illicit flows at the border through increased data availability, an increase in annual Border Force seizure rates is anticipated. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>48.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Home Office analysis suggests that relative to 2023-24<authorialNote marker="1"><p> 2023-24 = Q2 2023, Q3 2023, Q4 2023, and Q1 2024.</p></authorialNote>, a 10% increase in annual seizures could lead to the additional seizure of approximately 2,700kg of Class A drugs, amongst other additional seizures of illicit goods and the potential protection of government revenue. Similarly, if annual seizures were to increase further, a 30% or 50% annual increase in seizures could result in the seizure of 8,100kg and 14,000kg of Class A drugs, amongst other additional seizures and revenue protected.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>49.</num>
        <content>
          <p>While it is not possible to determine the likelihood of these scenarios occurring in practice, they provide an indication of the potential scale of impact that could be realised as a result of ENS introduction. In addition to revenue loss protection, there are likely to be associated socioeconomic benefits from increased seizures such as improvements in health outcomes as a result of preventing harmful illicit material (such as class A drugs) from entering the UK. Seizures of offensive weapons and lethal firearms may also prevent or reduce the harm caused by crimes in the UK. While it has not been possible to monetise them, it is worth noting these additional benefits.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
