      <paragraph>
        <num>51.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We do not apply any uplifts for changes in import levels in future years. This is because the volume of ENS declarations for non-EU imports has not increased despite the corresponding increase in the volume of imports. This could be due to importers modifying their behaviour so that they do not need to submit additional ENS declarations.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>52.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There is a high degree of uncertainty to several of the inputs and assumptions. Monte Carlo analysis of the model suggests that the factors most likely to influence the total estimated cost are the level of discount for high frequency submitters and whether there are calculable ENS costs for fast parcel operators. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Risks and assumptions</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>53.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There is limited evidence available on ENS declarations, so modelling assumptions have been made with varying degrees of uncertainty. These have been described throughout the text.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Impact on small and micro businesses</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>54.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The S&amp;S new model ensures that those businesses already set up to import from non-EU countries, or those submitting voluntarily on EU movements, do not need to make any changes to their existing systems or procedures if they do not wish to. Those businesses who will be required to complete ENS declarations for the first time (for example, those who only import from the EU) can choose to complete only the mandatory and any relevant conditional fields.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>55.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Using the ONS’s Interdepartmental Business Register matched at the enterprise level, we estimate that, 54% of ENS declarations from the EU would be for imports by large and medium businesses. We estimate 46% would be for imports by micro and small and sole trader businesses. This means that around half of the costs would be experienced by small and micro businesses (SMBs). </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>56.</num>
        <content>
          <p>HMRC has engaged extensively with businesses who are expecting and preparing for the end of the waiver.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>57.</num>
        <content>
          <p>On the other hand, as SMBs are more represented in trade with the EU, they will also experience relatively higher benefits due to the reduction in dataset size.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>58.</num>
        <content>
          <p>ENS declarations are required across all movements for the policy to work effectively. HMG would be unable to meet its objectives if a specific exemption were provided.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Wider impacts</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>59.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This measure will not directly impact individuals. ENS declarations are a requirement for businesses involved in the commercial movements of goods. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>60.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The competition assessment checklist has been completed for this measure as private industry, in the form of customs intermediaries, support businesses to complete ENS declarations. These measures will not limit the number or range of suppliers or impact the abilities or incentives for intermediaries to compete. Similarly, there will be no impact on the choices or information available to consumers. Therefore, no full competition impact assessment is required for this measure. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>61.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The environmental impacts are expected to be minimal as we do not foresee the end of the waiver having a significant impact on the volume of trade, and the environmental impact of completing and submitting the declarations themselves is likely to be small as they are digital declarations. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>62.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The facilitations will have a positive impact on Border Force intelligence and enforcement capability. The ability to collect S&amp;S data will enhance our intelligence on imported goods and help Border Force to keep UK citizens safe from the most harmful goods brought into the country. It will also minimise disruption at the border by supporting a more intelligence-informed approach to risking and intervention, as well as facilitating the flow of legitimate trade by reducing the number of ‘false positive’ hits.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>A summary of the potential trade implications of measure</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>63.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We do not expect this measure to have a significant impact on trade. S&amp;S declarations are used globally to risk-assess movements being imported and exported to prevent illicit goods entering. ENS declarations and Exit Summary (EXS) declarations (a type of S&amp;S declaration for export) have been required for trade with non-EU countries since 2011. EXS declarations have been required for GB exports into the EU since 1 October 2021. The EU has required both ENS and EXS declarations on trade with GB since 1 January 2021.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>64.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The previous government worked closely with industry to develop an approach that balances the security benefits with the additional burden placed on businesses. We are aware that some businesses will be required to submit ENS declarations for the first time. HMG continues to engage with industry so they are ready to start meeting these new requirements. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Monitoring and evaluation</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>65.</num>
        <content>
          <p>  The monitoring and evaluation of the strategy will follow the guidance of the Green Book (HMT, 2023) and the Magenta Book (2022). This will encompass a range of evaluation approaches including process, outcomes, outputs, impacts, learning and accountability. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>66.</num>
        <content>
          <p>More specifically, the impact of these arrangements will be monitored through ongoing engagement with affected businesses, and discussion of how these requirements affect them. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>67.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We will monitor the number of ENS declarations received, with the expectation that the volume received for these types of movements will increase, reflecting the ENS declarations for imports from the EU coming in after the removal of the waiver. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>68.</num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Annex A: Data sources used.</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Customs Handling of Import and Export Freight (CHIEF) and Customs Declaration Service (CDS): Customs declarations data (2021 and 2022)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>69.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This is the primary source used to estimate the volume of EU ENS declarations; since customs import declarations have a good correspondence with ENS declarations and have been required on imports from the EU since 2021. We also use this to segment the population and also estimate breakdowns by transport mode, and for secondary analysis such as the timing of declaration submission. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>S&amp;S GB: S&amp;S data for movements from non-EU countries (2021 and 2022)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>70.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This is used as a baseline for future non-EU S&amp;S volumes. We also use this to estimate EU S&amp;S volumes for freight remaining on board (FROB), as well as for inbound empty units. S&amp;S GB data is also used to estimate breakdowns of consignment type, such as whether it corresponds to a parcel movement. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>New Computerised Transit System: Transit declarations. (2021)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>71.</num>
        <content>
          <p>These are also used in the volume of EU ENS declarations, since customs declarations will not necessarily exist for these movements. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>HMRC Customs Intermediaries Survey: costs information (2021)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>72.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This HMRC commissioned survey, carried out by Ipsos Mori, is used to build cost estimates, with data on time to complete declarations and fees charged.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Commercial pricing information (2022)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>73.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We use commercially advertised prices online to build into cost estimates and to estimate the level of bulk discount. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>HMRC analysis of Staged Customs Controls (2021-22)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>74.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Used to adjust for a one-off policy which meant customs declarations were received in 2022 which were for imports made in 2021. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Industry and stakeholder engagement (2022)</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>75.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Used for pricing of parcels and to support bulk discounts estimate.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
